Today's adventure: squash a bug üêõüí•

Started out with tiny fix-up to do on an old website and run into a wild bug: some of desktop menu items refused to show their pages! ü§î Mobile menu? No problemo! üì± Desktop menu - problemo! üïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

First stop: Admin panel. üõ†Ô∏è Oh, desktop menu is missing some of the hrefs that the mobile menu has. Let's put them in. All good now? No sir! üòÖ

Next up: diving into the code. Oh, the main menu template has an `if` statement: if an item has a submenu, this item does not get an `<a href>` tag. Is it supposed to be like this? Evidently not. Added those bad boys in. üíª Easy fix, or so I thought. üò¨

The correct hrefs are now in place! But... click on them - nothing happens. Why? üò± 

Turns out, a legacy beast (jQuery) overrides the clicks! ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Do I want to mess with this legacy code? Care to wake the dragon? üêâ

Is there a way around? Let's see if we can restructure the HTML. Does not work the first time... but works the second time! Tested and retested across desktop and mobile‚Äîvoil√†, it works like a charm! üé©‚ú®

Remember R. Martin quoting his boss in Clean Code: "Bugs aren't 'interesting.' They just have to be fixed." Well, some bugs do have a hint of intrigue, but shh, don't tell the boss! üòâü§´

